node.text:
Average duration of a human blink: 0.25 seconds.

A lot can happen in the blink of an eye.

Across the universe 15,000 stars will be born and 300 star will explode. 
15,000,000 rogue planets will form. 

The sun will burn 175,000,000 tons of hydrogen and produce 96,100,000,000,000,00,000,000,000 joules of energy.

30 black holes will be born. 

The universe will expand by 527,250 kilometers. 

Our galaxy will travel 250 kilometers and grow by 125 meters. 

The Andromeda galaxy will get 27 kilometers closer and light will travel 74,948 kilometers. 

Approximate number of blinks in a human lifetime: 650,000,000. 

Think next time you blink.

 🌌 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature 🔭

Do you love Universe ❤

Are you ready to explore Space 🔭 @TheOurSpace

Image credit: @melodysheep_

node.text:
Everyone knows which planets have rings: it's Saturn, Neptune, and Uranus. But there's one more you may not be aware of. Jupiter has rings too, although they're so faint, it took a spacecraft to find them (NASA's Voyager 1 mission in 1980). Until 1979, astronomers had no idea that wispy rings of dust and rock particles encircled our solar system's largest gas giant. That's because unlike the rings of Saturn, which are made of relatively large pieces of ice that reflect sunlight, Jupiter's rings are made of miniscule particles of rock and dust — some as small as cigarette-smoke particles — which makes them dark and nearly impossible to see from Earth. 🌌 🔭 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature

node.text:
Earth as seen from the surface of Mars, shining brighter than any star in the Martian night sky. This picture was taken by NASA's Curiosity rover. 

The Curiosity rover captured the setting of Phobos on Mars in the vicinity of Mount Sharp.
Phobos is one of the two satellites of Mars, but in the sky of the red planet, it looks completely different from the Moon in the sky of the Earth. The diameter of Phobos is 125 times smaller than the diameter of the Moon. In addition, in the Martian sky, Phobos rises in the west and sets in the east.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The tidal effect of Mars gradually slows down the movement of Phobos and in the future will lead to its fall on the planet or destruction with the formation of a planetary ring. Already now Phobos is at a distance 40 times less than the distance from the Earth to the Moon. But that's why you can see it at least a little.🔭 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature 🔭
